title: For Sale:  Springfield M1A "Loaded" model with 13 magazines & amenities
location: Apex, NC, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
This is a RIFLEMAN's rifle.  This loaded M1A shines out to and beyond 500 yards. I am doing some consolidation and it is time to find her a loving home. She comes with 13 magazines and a pouch. 

This rifle comes as you see it here and will ship in its original Springfield Armory factory box.
Specifications:
 - This is a Springfield Armory "Loaded" model M1A
 - GI walnut stock.
 - 2-stage match grade trigger.
 - National Match front sight blade.
 - GI Match Grade rear aperture with 1/2 MOA windage adjustments.
 - Stainless steel 22" National Match barrel (labeled "NM .308 SS")
 - It has an upgraded GI extractor and spring
 - 12x 20-round GI magazines, blued (New manufacture, Like new condition)  ($240 value)
 - 1x 10-round factory magazine with parkerized finish
 - Magazine pouch for the buttstock ($20 value)
 - Cleaning kit inside buttstock ($20 value)
 - M14 GI sling, nylon

The first owner of this rifle bought it to hunt with.  He soon realized that a Battle Rifle is not necessarily an ideal deer rifle.  :-)  That is when he sold it to me.  He had very few rounds through it.   I have had this rifle for almost 7 years.  I have put approximately 800 rounds through it.  I added the GI extractor, mag pouch, and cleaning kit. I also painted in the numbers on dials of the rear sight so you can read the elevation and windage markings clearly.

Someone asked me how far out I have shot it.
I have shot it out to 500 yards.  When I am doing my part, it shoots 2-3 moa with NATO mil-surp ammo.  There is a range out in Ramseur, NC where the Appleseed clinics are held.  So after qualifying, I was able to go up to their full-length range which has targets at 200, 300, 400, and 500.  With South African Nato 7.62x51 ammo, the rifle is dead-balls-on at 200, 300, 400, and 500 yards.  You just gotta dial it in and do your part... and it hits where it should.  

The elevation knob does go to 1000 as I recall. It would be really cool to take it up to Camp Butner and see what she does out to 1000 yards.  It might be a lot to ask of a 147 grain mil-spec projectile... but the 168 Federal Gold Match round was made with the M1A in mind and it will do it.
